{{Citation needed|date=July 2020}} '''Tenmonkata''' (天文方) was the astronomical and calendrical research institution established by the [[Tokugawa Shogunate]]. Its primary responsibility was overseeing the creation of calendars ({{ill|Henreki|ja|編暦|qq=draft|qq=draft}}).
== Overview ==
Initially, calendar creation was the responsibility of the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a bureau under the {{ill|Imperial Court (Japan)|ja|朝廷|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and supervised by the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. However, in the first year of {{ill|Jōkyō|ja|貞享|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (1684), {{ill|Shibukawa Shunkai|ja|渋川春海|qq=draft|qq=draft}} created the {{ill|Jōkyō calendar|ja|貞享暦|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, replacing the traditional {{ill|Senmyō calendar|ja|宣明暦|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Following this achievement, the Shogunate established the Tenmonkata under the supervision of the {{ill|Jisha Bugyō|ja|寺社奉行|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. On {{ill|December 1, 1684|ja|貞享元年12月1日|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (January 5, 1685), Shunkai was appointed the first Tenmonkata, which also became the name of the role. Calendar-making responsibilities shifted from the Imperial Court to the Shogunate, and the Tenmonkata carried out its tasks under Shogunate authority. Initially under the Jisha Bugyō, it was placed under the {{ill|Wakadoshiyori|ja|若年寄|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on {{ill|January 23, 1747|ja|延享4th year 1月23日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
The position was hereditary, but capable individuals with expertise in astronomy were occasionally appointed through adoption or special selection. By the end of the Edo period, eight families held the position: the {{ill|Shibukawa family|ja|渋川家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Inokai family|ja|猪飼家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nishikawa family|ja|西川家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yamaji family|ja|山路家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yoshida family|ja|吉田家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Okumura family|ja|奥村家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Takahashi family|ja|高橋家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Adachi family|ja|足立家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Some families, such as those of {{ill|Nishikawa Joken|ja|西川如見|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Takahashi Yoshitoki|ja|高橋至時|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, did not maintain their roles until the end of the period. By the late Edo period, only the Shibukawa, Yamaji, and Adachi families continued in the position.
In the 8th year of {{ill|Bunka|ja|文化|1=Bunka|2=ja|3=文化 (元号)|4=de|5=Bunka (Ära)|6=ko|7=분카|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (1811), {{ill|Takahashi Kageyasu|ja|高橋景保|qq=draft|qq=draft}} proposed establishing the {{ill|Bansho Wage Goyo|ja|蛮書和解御用|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which lasted until the establishment of the {{ill|Institute for Western Studies|ja|蕃書調所|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Ansei|ja|安政|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 3 (1858). By the late Edo period, the Tenmonkata also handled astronomical observations, surveying, geography, and the translation of Western books, serving as one of the predecessors of {{ill|The University of Tokyo|ja|東京大学|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
