In the 8th year of {{ill|Bunka|ja|文化|1=Bunka|2=ja|3=文化 (元号)|4=de|5=Bunka (Ära)|6=ko|7=분카|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (1811), {{ill|Takahashi Kageyasu|ja|高橋景保|qq=draft|qq=draft}} proposed establishing the {{ill|Bansho Wage Goyo|ja|蛮書和解御用|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which lasted until the establishment of the {{ill|Institute for Western Studies|ja|蕃書調所|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Ansei|ja|安政|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 3 (1858). By the late Edo period, the Tenmonkata also handled astronomical observations, surveying, geography, and the translation of Western books, serving as one of the predecessors of {{ill|The University of Tokyo|ja|東京大学|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== The Tenmonkata Families ==

; Shibukawa Family
: Owing to Shibukawa Shunkai's achievements, his family assumed the role of Tenmonkata in Jōkyō 1 (1684) and maintained the position, despite several adoptions, until the late Edo period.
: {{ill|Shibukawa Shunkai|ja|渋川春海|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Mukai|ja|渋川昔尹|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiin|ja|渋川敬尹|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiya|ja|渋川敬也|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Noriyasu|ja|渋川則休|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Mitsuhiro|ja|渋川光洪|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Masakiyo|ja|渋川正清|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Masayō|ja|渋川正陽|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiyū|ja|渋川景佑|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – ({{ill|Shibukawa Keichoku|ja|渋川敬直|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) – {{ill|Shibukawa Sukemasa|ja|渋川佑賢|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiten|ja|渋川敬典|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

; Inokai Family
: {{ill|Inokai Masakazu|ja|猪飼正一|qq=draft|qq=draft}} became Tenmonkata in {{ill|Kyōhō|ja|享保|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (1716). After his death in {{ill|Kanpō|ja|寛保|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (1741), the family ceased its role.

; Nishikawa Family
: Nishikawa Joken’s son, {{ill|Nishikawa Masayasu|ja|西川正休|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, was appointed in {{ill|Enkyō|ja|延享|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 4 (1747). The position lasted for two generations.
: {{ill|Nishikawa Masayasu|ja|西川正休|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Nishikawa Tadataka|ja|西川忠喬|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

; Yamaji Family
: {{ill|Yamaji Sukezumi|ja|山路主住|qq=draft|qq=draft}} became Tenmonkata in {{ill|Meiwa|ja|明和|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (1764). His descendants continued until the end of the Edo period.
: {{ill|Yamaji Sukezumi|ja|山路主住|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – ({{ill|Yamaji Yukiyuki|ja|山路之徽|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) – {{ill|Yamaji Tokufū|ja|山路徳風|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Yamaji Kanetaka|ja|山路諧孝|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Yamaji Akitsune|ja|山路彰常|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – ({{ill|Yamaji Akizumi|ja|山路彰善|qq=draft|qq=draft}})

; Yoshida Family
: {{ill|Sasaki Nagahide|ja|佐々木長秀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, later {{ill|Yoshida Nagahide|ja|吉田秀長|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, became Tenmonkata in {{ill|Meiwa|ja|明和|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (1764).
: {{ill|Yoshida Nagahide|ja|吉田秀長|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀升|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀賢|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀茂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

== Observatories ==
The first observatory, '''Sitendai''', was established in {{ill|Jōkyō|ja|貞享|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2 (1685) in {{ill|Ushigome Wakamachi|ja|牛込藁町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It moved to {{ill|Kanda Surugadai|ja|神田駿河台|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 14 (1701) and later to {{ill|Asakusa|ja|浅草|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In {{ill|Tenpō|ja|天保|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 13 (1842), a second observatory was established in {{ill|Kudanzaka|ja|九段坂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Both were abolished in {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2 (1869).

== Abolition of the Tenmonkata ==
After the {{ill|Taisei Hōkan|ja|大政奉還|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, responsibility for calendrical work returned to the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 3 (1870), calendrical duties were transferred to the Ministry of Education's {{ill|Astronomical Bureau|ja|天文暦道局|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

