{{Citation needed|date=July 2020}}
'''Tenmonkata''' (天文方) was the astronomical and calendrical research institution established by the [[Tokugawa shogunate|Tokugawa Shogunate]]. Its primary responsibility was overseeing the creation of calendars ({{ill|Henreki|ja|編暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Henreki|qq=}}).

== Overview ==

Initially, calendar creation was the responsibility of the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōryō|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang Bureau|qq=}}, a bureau under the {{ill|Imperial Court (Japan)|ja|朝廷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Court (Japan)|qq=}} and supervised by the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado family|qq=}}. However, in the first year of {{ill|Jōkyō|ja|貞享|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkyō|qq=}} (1684), {{ill|Shibukawa Shunkai|ja|渋川春海|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Shunkai|qq=}} created the {{ill|Jōkyō calendar|ja|貞享暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkyō calendar|qq=}}, replacing the traditional {{ill|Senmyō calendar|ja|宣明暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senmyō calendar|qq=}}. Following this achievement, the Shogunate established the Tenmonkata under the supervision of the {{ill|Jisha Bugyō|ja|寺社奉行|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jisha Bugyō|qq=}}. On {{ill|December 1, 1684|ja|貞享元年12月1日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/December 1, 1684|qq=}} (January 5, 1685), Shunkai was appointed the first Tenmonkata, which also became the name of the role. Calendar-making responsibilities shifted from the Imperial Court to the Shogunate, and the Tenmonkata carried out its tasks under Shogunate authority. Initially under the Jisha Bugyō, it was placed under the {{ill|Wakadoshiyori|ja|若年寄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakadoshiyori|qq=}} on {{ill|January 23, 1747|ja|延享4th year 1月23日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 23, 1747|qq=}}.

The position was hereditary, but capable individuals with expertise in astronomy were occasionally appointed through adoption or special selection. By the end of the Edo period, eight families held the position: the {{ill|Shibukawa family|ja|渋川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa family|qq=}}, {{ill|Inokai family|ja|猪飼家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inokai family|qq=}}, {{ill|Nishikawa family|ja|西川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa family|qq=}}, {{ill|Yamaji family|ja|山路家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji family|qq=}}, {{ill|Yoshida family|ja|吉田家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida family|qq=}}, {{ill|Okumura family|ja|奥村家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okumura family|qq=}}, {{ill|Takahashi family|ja|高橋家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takahashi family|qq=}}, and {{ill|Adachi family|ja|足立家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Adachi family|qq=}}. Some families, such as those of {{ill|Nishikawa Joken|ja|西川如見|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Joken|qq=}} and {{ill|Takahashi Yoshitoki|ja|高橋至時|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takahashi Yoshitoki|qq=}}, did not maintain their roles until the end of the period. By the late Edo period, only the Shibukawa, Yamaji, and Adachi families continued in the position.

In the 8th year of {{ill|Bunka|ja|文化 (元号)|ja|文化|1=Bunka|2=ja|3=文化 (元号)|4=de|5=Bunka (Ära)|6=ko|7=분카|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunka|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunka|qq=}} (1811), {{ill|Takahashi Kageyasu|ja|高橋景保|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takahashi Kageyasu|qq=}} proposed establishing the {{ill|Bansho Wage Goyo|ja|蛮書和解御用|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bansho Wage Goyo|qq=}}, which lasted until the establishment of the {{ill|Institute for Western Studies|ja|蕃書調所|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Institute for Western Studies|qq=}} in {{ill|Ansei|ja|安政|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ansei|qq=}} 3 (1858). By the late Edo period, the Tenmonkata also handled astronomical observations, surveying, geography, and the translation of Western books, serving as one of the predecessors of {{ill|The University of Tokyo|ja|東京大学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/The University of Tokyo|qq=}}.

== The Tenmonkata Families ==

; Shibukawa Family
: Owing to Shibukawa Shunkai's achievements, his family assumed the role of Tenmonkata in Jōkyō 1 (1684) and maintained the position, despite several adoptions, until the late Edo period.
: {{ill|Shibukawa Shunkai|ja|渋川春海|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Shunkai|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Mukai|ja|渋川昔尹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Mukai|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiin|ja|渋川敬尹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiin|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiya|ja|渋川敬也|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiya|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Noriyasu|ja|渋川則休|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Noriyasu|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Mitsuhiro|ja|渋川光洪|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Mitsuhiro|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Masakiyo|ja|渋川正清|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Masakiyo|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Masayō|ja|渋川正陽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Masayō|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiyū|ja|渋川景佑|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiyū|qq=}} – ({{ill|Shibukawa Keichoku|ja|渋川敬直|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keichoku|qq=}}) – {{ill|Shibukawa Sukemasa|ja|渋川佑賢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Sukemasa|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiten|ja|渋川敬典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiten|qq=}}

; Inokai Family
: {{ill|Inokai Masakazu|ja|猪飼正一|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inokai Masakazu|qq=}} became Tenmonkata in {{ill|Kyōhō|ja|享保|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyōhō|qq=}} 1 (1716). After his death in {{ill|Kanpō|ja|寛保|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanpō|qq=}} 1 (1741), the family ceased its role.

; Nishikawa Family
: Nishikawa Joken’s son, {{ill|Nishikawa Masayasu|ja|西川正休|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Masayasu|qq=}}, was appointed in {{ill|Enkyō|ja|延享|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enkyō|qq=}} 4 (1747). The position lasted for two generations.
: {{ill|Nishikawa Masayasu|ja|西川正休|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Masayasu|qq=}} – {{ill|Nishikawa Tadataka|ja|西川忠喬|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Tadataka|qq=}}

; Yamaji Family
: {{ill|Yamaji Sukezumi|ja|山路主住|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Sukezumi|qq=}} became Tenmonkata in {{ill|Meiwa|ja|明和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiwa|qq=}} 1 (1764). His descendants continued until the end of the Edo period.
: {{ill|Yamaji Sukezumi|ja|山路主住|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Sukezumi|qq=}} – ({{ill|Yamaji Yukiyuki|ja|山路之徽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Yukiyuki|qq=}}) – {{ill|Yamaji Tokufū|ja|山路徳風|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Tokufū|qq=}} – {{ill|Yamaji Kanetaka|ja|山路諧孝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Kanetaka|qq=}} – {{ill|Yamaji Akitsune|ja|山路彰常|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Akitsune|qq=}} – ({{ill|Yamaji Akizumi|ja|山路彰善|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Akizumi|qq=}})

; Yoshida Family
: {{ill|Sasaki Nagahide|ja|佐々木長秀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sasaki Nagahide|qq=}}, later {{ill|Yoshida Nagahide|ja|吉田秀長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Nagahide|qq=}}, became Tenmonkata in {{ill|Meiwa|ja|明和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiwa|qq=}} 1 (1764).
: {{ill|Yoshida Nagahide|ja|吉田秀長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Nagahide|qq=}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀升|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Hideaki|qq=}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀賢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Hideaki|qq=}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀茂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Hideaki|qq=}}

== Observatories ==
The first observatory, '''Sitendai''', was established in {{ill|Jōkyō|ja|貞享|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkyō|qq=}} 2 (1685) in {{ill|Ushigome Wakamachi|ja|牛込藁町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ushigome Wakamachi|qq=}}. It moved to {{ill|Kanda Surugadai|ja|神田駿河台|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanda Surugadai|qq=}} in {{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genroku|qq=}} 14 (1701) and later to {{ill|Asakusa|ja|浅草|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asakusa|qq=}}. In {{ill|Tenpō|ja|天保|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpō|qq=}} 13 (1842), a second observatory was established in {{ill|Kudanzaka|ja|九段坂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kudanzaka|qq=}}. Both were abolished in {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 2 (1869).

== Abolition of the Tenmonkata ==
After the {{ill|Taisei Hōkan|ja|大政奉還|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taisei Hōkan|qq=}}, responsibility for calendrical work returned to the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado family|qq=}}. In {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 3 (1870), calendrical duties were transferred to the Ministry of Education's {{ill|Astronomical Bureau|ja|天文暦道局|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Astronomical Bureau|qq=}}.

