'''Tenmonkata''' (天文方) was the astronomical and calendrical research institution established by the [[Tokugawa shogunate|Tokugawa Shogunate]]. Its primary responsibility was overseeing the creation of calendars ({{ill|Henreki|ja|編暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Henreki|qq=}}).

== Overview ==

Initially, calendar creation was the responsibility of the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōryō|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang Bureau|qq=}}, a bureau under the {{ill|Imperial Court (Japan)|ja|朝廷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Court (Japan)|qq=}} and supervised by the {{ill|Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado family|qq=}}. However, in the first year of {{ill|Jōkyō|ja|貞享|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkyō|qq=}} (1684), {{ill|Shibukawa Shunkai|ja|渋川春海|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Shunkai|qq=}} created the {{ill|Jōkyō calendar|ja|貞享暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkyō calendar|qq=}}, replacing the traditional {{ill|Senmyō calendar|ja|宣明暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senmyō calendar|qq=}}. Following this achievement, the Shogunate established the Tenmonkata under the supervision of the {{ill|Jisha Bugyō|ja|寺社奉行|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jisha Bugyō|qq=}}. On {{ill|December 1, 1684|ja|貞享元年12月1日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/December 1, 1684|qq=}} (January 5, 1685), Shunkai was appointed the first Tenmonkata, which also became the name of the role. Calendar-making responsibilities shifted from the Imperial Court to the Shogunate, and the Tenmonkata carried out its tasks under Shogunate authority. Initially under the Jisha Bugyō, it was placed under the {{ill|Wakadoshiyori|ja|若年寄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakadoshiyori|qq=}} on {{ill|January 23, 1747|ja|延享4th year 1月23日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 23, 1747|qq=}}.

The position was hereditary, but capable individuals with expertise in astronomy were occasionally appointed through adoption or special selection. By the end of the Edo period, eight families held the position: the {{ill|Shibukawa family|ja|渋川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa family|qq=}}, {{ill|Inokai family|ja|猪飼家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inokai family|qq=}}, {{ill|Nishikawa family|ja|西川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa family|qq=}}, {{ill|Yamaji family|ja|山路家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji family|qq=}}, {{ill|Urabe clan|lt=Urabe clan|lt=Yoshida family|ja|吉田家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida family|qq=}}, {{ill|Okumura family|ja|奥村家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okumura family|qq=}}, {{ill|Takahashi family|ja|高橋家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takahashi family|qq=}}, and {{ill|Adachi family|ja|足立家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Adachi family|qq=}}. Some families, such as those of {{ill|Nishikawa Joken|ja|西川如見|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Joken|qq=}} and {{ill|Takahashi Yoshitoki|ja|高橋至時|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takahashi Yoshitoki|qq=}}, did not maintain their roles until the end of the period. By the late Edo period, only the Shibukawa, Yamaji, and Adachi families continued in the position.

In the 8th year of {{ill|Bunka|ja|文化 (元号)|ja|文化|1=Bunka|2=ja|3=文化 (元号)|4=de|5=Bunka (Ära)|6=ko|7=분카|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunka|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunka|qq=}} (1811), {{ill|Takahashi Kageyasu|ja|高橋景保|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takahashi Kageyasu|qq=}} proposed establishing the {{ill|Bansho Wage Goyo|ja|蛮書和解御用|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bansho Wage Goyo|qq=}}, which lasted until the establishment of the {{ill|Institute for Western Studies|ja|蕃書調所|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Institute for Western Studies|qq=}} in {{ill|Ansei|ja|安政|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ansei|qq=}} 3 (1858). By the late Edo period, the Tenmonkata also handled astronomical observations, surveying, geography, and the translation of Western books, serving as one of the predecessors of {{ill|The University of Tokyo|ja|東京大学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/The University of Tokyo|qq=}}.

