; Shibukawa Family : Owing to Shibukawa Shunkai's achievements, his family assumed the role of Tenmonkata in Jōkyō 1 (1684) and maintained the position, despite several adoptions, until the late Edo period. : [[:en:Shibukawa Shunkai|Shibukawa Shunkai]] – {{ill|Shibukawa Mukai|ja|渋川昔尹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Mukai|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiin|ja|渋川敬尹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiin|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiya|ja|渋川敬也|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiya|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Noriyasu|ja|渋川則休|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Noriyasu|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Mitsuhiro|ja|渋川光洪|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Mitsuhiro|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Masakiyo|ja|渋川正清|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Masakiyo|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Masayō|ja|渋川正陽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Masayō|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiyū|ja|渋川景佑|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiyū|qq=}} – ({{ill|Shibukawa Keichoku|ja|渋川敬直|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keichoku|qq=}}) – {{ill|Shibukawa Sukemasa|ja|渋川佑賢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Sukemasa|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiten|ja|渋川敬典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiten|qq=}}
; Inokai Family : {{ill|Inokai Masakazu|ja|猪飼正一|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inokai Masakazu|qq=}} became Tenmonkata in [[:en:Kyōhō|Kyōhō]] 1 (1716). After his death in [[:en:Kanpō|Kanpō]] 1 (1741), the family ceased its role.
; Nishikawa Family : Nishikawa Joken’s son, {{ill|Nishikawa Masayasu|ja|西川正休|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Masayasu|qq=}}, was appointed in [[:en:Enkyō (Edo period)|Enkyō]] 4 (1747). The position lasted for two generations. : {{ill|Nishikawa Masayasu|ja|西川正休|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Masayasu|qq=}} – {{ill|Nishikawa Tadataka|ja|西川忠喬|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Tadataka|qq=}}
; Yamaji Family : [[:en:Yamaji Nushizumi|Yamaji Sukezumi]] became Tenmonkata in [[:en:Meiwa|Meiwa]] 1 (1764). His descendants continued until the end of the Edo period. : [[:en:Yamaji Nushizumi|Yamaji Sukezumi]] – ({{ill|Yamaji Yukiyuki|ja|山路之徽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Yukiyuki|qq=}}) – {{ill|Yamaji Tokufū|ja|山路徳風|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Tokufū|qq=}} – {{ill|Yamaji Kanetaka|ja|山路諧孝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Kanetaka|qq=}} – {{ill|Yamaji Akitsune|ja|山路彰常|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Akitsune|qq=}} – ({{ill|Yamaji Akizumi|ja|山路彰善|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Akizumi|qq=}})
; Yoshida Family : {{ill|Sasaki Nagahide|ja|佐々木長秀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sasaki Nagahide|qq=}}, later {{ill|Yoshida Nagahide|ja|吉田秀長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Nagahide|qq=}}, became Tenmonkata in [[:en:Meiwa|Meiwa]] 1 (1764). : {{ill|Yoshida Nagahide|ja|吉田秀長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Nagahide|qq=}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀升|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Hideaki|qq=}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀賢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Hideaki|qq=}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀茂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Hideaki|qq=}}
== Observatories == The first observatory, '''Sitendai''', was established in [[:en:Jōkyō|Jōkyō]] 2 (1685) in {{ill|Ushigome Wakamachi|ja|牛込藁町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ushigome Wakamachi|qq=}}. It moved to [[:en:Surugadai|Kanda Surugadai]] in [[:en:Genroku|Genroku]] 14 (1701) and later to [[:en:Asakusa|Asakusa]]. In [[:en:Tenpō|Tenpō]] 13 (1842), a second observatory was established in {{ill|Kudanzaka|ja|九段坂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kudanzaka|qq=}}. Both were abolished in [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 2 (1869).
