<!--Tenmongata--><!--Tenmongata--><!--Tenmongata--><!--Tenmongata--><!--Tenmongata--><!--Tenmongata--><!--Tenmongata--><!--Tenmongata--> [[Category:17th-century Japanese astronomers]] [[Category:18th-century Japanese astronomers]] [[Category:19th-century Japanese astronomers]] [[Category:天文学に関する記事]] [[Category:山路家]] [[Category:History of astronomy in Japan]] [[Category:Calendars]] [[Category:江戸幕府の学校・研究機関]] [[Category:江戸幕府の職制]] [[Category:江戸時代の天文学]] [[Category:江戸時代の天文学者]] [[Category:渋川家]]

{{Citation needed|date=July 2020}} '''Tenmonkata''' (天文方) was the astronomical and calendrical research institution established by the [[Tokugawa shogunate|Tokugawa Shogunate]]. Its primary responsibility was overseeing the creation of calendars ({{ill|Henreki|ja|編暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Henreki|qq=}}).
== Overview ==
Initially, calendar creation was the responsibility of the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōryō|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang Bureau|qq=}}, a bureau under the [[:en:Royal court|Imperial Court (Japan)]] and supervised by the {{ill|Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado family|qq=}}. However, in the first year of [[:en:Jōkyō|Jōkyō]] (1684), [[:en:Shibukawa Shunkai|Shibukawa Shunkai]] created the [[:en:Jōkyō calendar|Jōkyō calendar]], replacing the traditional [[:en:Xuanming calendar|Senmyō calendar]]. Following this achievement, the Shogunate established the Tenmonkata under the supervision of the [[:en:Jisha-bugyō|Jisha Bugyō]]. On {{ill|December 1, 1684|ja|貞享元年12月1日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/December 1, 1684|qq=}} (January 5, 1685), Shunkai was appointed the first Tenmonkata, which also became the name of the role. Calendar-making responsibilities shifted from the Imperial Court to the Shogunate, and the Tenmonkata carried out its tasks under Shogunate authority. Initially under the Jisha Bugyō, it was placed under the [[:en:Wakadoshiyori|Wakadoshiyori]] on {{ill|January 23, 1747|ja|延享4th year 1月23日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 23, 1747|qq=}}.
The position was hereditary, but capable individuals with expertise in astronomy were occasionally appointed through adoption or special selection. By the end of the Edo period, eight families held the position: the {{ill|Shibukawa family|ja|渋川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa family|qq=}}, {{ill|Inokai family|ja|猪飼家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inokai family|qq=}}, {{ill|Nishikawa family|ja|西川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa family|qq=}}, {{ill|Yamaji family|ja|山路家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji family|qq=}}, {{ill|Urabe clan|lt=Urabe clan|lt=Yoshida family|ja|吉田家|1=Urabe clan|2=ja|3=卜部氏|lt=Yoshida family|comment=Might be more of a redirect with potential but this is strictly potential right now|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida family|qq=}}, {{ill|Okumura family|ja|奥村家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okumura family|qq=}}, {{ill|Takahashi family|ja|高橋家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takahashi family|qq=}}, and {{ill|Adachi family|ja|足立家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Adachi family|qq=}}. Some families, such as those of [[:en:Nishikawa Joken|Nishikawa Joken]] and [[:en:Takahashi Yoshitoki|Takahashi Yoshitoki]], did not maintain their roles until the end of the period. By the late Edo period, only the Shibukawa, Yamaji, and Adachi families continued in the position.
In the 8th year of [[:en:Culture|Bunka]] (1811), {{ill|Takahashi Kageyasu|ja|高橋景保|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takahashi Kageyasu|qq=}} proposed establishing the {{ill|Bansho Wage Goyo|ja|蛮書和解御用|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bansho Wage Goyo|qq=}}, which lasted until the establishment of the [[:en:Bansho Shirabesho|Institute for Western Studies]] in [[:en:Ansei|Ansei]] 3 (1858). By the late Edo period, the Tenmonkata also handled astronomical observations, surveying, geography, and the translation of Western books, serving as one of the predecessors of [[:en:University of Tokyo|The University of Tokyo]].
