The position was hereditary, but capable individuals with expertise in astronomy were occasionally appointed through adoption or special selection. By the end of the Edo period, eight families held the position: the {{ill|Shibukawa family|ja|渋川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa family|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, {{ill|Inokai family|ja|猪飼家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inokai family|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, {{ill|Nishikawa family|ja|西川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa family|qq=}}, {{ill|Yamaji family|ja|山路家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji family|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, {{ill|Urabe clan|lt=Urabe clan|lt=Yoshida family|ja|吉田家|1=Urabe clan|2=ja|3=卜部氏|lt=Yoshida family|comment=Might be more of a redirect with potential but this is strictly potential right now|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida family|qq=}}, {{ill|Okumura family|ja|奥村家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okumura family|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 奥村氏}}, {{ill|Takahashi family|ja|高橋家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takahashi family|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, and {{ill|Adachi family|ja|足立家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Adachi family|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. Some families, such as those of [[:en:Nishikawa Joken|Nishikawa Joken]] and [[:en:Takahashi Yoshitoki|Takahashi Yoshitoki]], did not maintain their roles until the end of the period. By the late Edo period, only the Shibukawa, Yamaji, and Adachi families continued in the position.
In the 8th year of [[:en:Culture|Bunka]] (1811), {{ill|Takahashi Kageyasu|ja|高橋景保|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takahashi Kageyasu|qq=}} proposed establishing the {{ill|Bansho Wage Goyo|ja|蛮書和解御用|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bansho Wage Goyo|qq=}}, which lasted until the establishment of the [[:en:Bansho Shirabesho|Institute for Western Studies]] in [[:en:Ansei|Ansei]] 3 (1858). By the late Edo period, the Tenmonkata also handled astronomical observations, surveying, geography, and the translation of Western books, serving as one of the predecessors of [[:en:University of Tokyo|The University of Tokyo]].
== The Tenmonkata Families ==
; Shibukawa Family : Owing to Shibukawa Shunkai's achievements, his family assumed the role of Tenmonkata in Jōkyō 1 (1684) and maintained the position, despite several adoptions, until the late Edo period. : [[:en:Shibukawa Shunkai|Shibukawa Shunkai]] – {{ill|Shibukawa Mukai|ja|渋川昔尹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Mukai|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiin|ja|渋川敬尹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiin|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiya|ja|渋川敬也|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiya|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 入間川重恒}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Noriyasu|ja|渋川則休|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Noriyasu|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Mitsuhiro|ja|渋川光洪|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Mitsuhiro|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Masakiyo|ja|渋川正清|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Masakiyo|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Masayō|ja|渋川正陽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Masayō|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiyū|ja|渋川景佑|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiyū|qq=}} – ({{ill|Shibukawa Keichoku|ja|渋川敬直|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keichoku|qq=}}) – {{ill|Shibukawa Sukemasa|ja|渋川佑賢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Sukemasa|qq=}} – {{ill|Shibukawa Keiten|ja|渋川敬典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibukawa Keiten|qq=}}
; Inokai Family : {{ill|Inokai Masakazu|ja|猪飼正一|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inokai Masakazu|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} became Tenmonkata in [[:en:Kyōhō|Kyōhō]] 1 (1716). After his death in [[:en:Kanpō|Kanpō]] 1 (1741), the family ceased its role.
; Nishikawa Family : Nishikawa Joken’s son, {{ill|Nishikawa Masayasu|ja|西川正休|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Masayasu|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 西川如見}}, was appointed in [[:en:Enkyō (Edo period)|Enkyō]] 4 (1747). The position lasted for two generations. : {{ill|Nishikawa Masayasu|ja|西川正休|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Masayasu|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 西川如見}} – {{ill|Nishikawa Tadataka|ja|西川忠喬|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikawa Tadataka|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}
; Yamaji Family : [[:en:Yamaji Nushizumi|Yamaji Sukezumi]] became Tenmonkata in [[:en:Meiwa|Meiwa]] 1 (1764). His descendants continued until the end of the Edo period. : [[:en:Yamaji Nushizumi|Yamaji Sukezumi]] – ({{ill|Yamaji Yukiyuki|ja|山路之徽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Yukiyuki|qq=}}) – {{ill|Yamaji Tokufū|ja|山路徳風|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Tokufū|qq=}} – {{ill|Yamaji Kanetaka|ja|山路諧孝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Kanetaka|qq=}} – {{ill|Yamaji Akitsune|ja|山路彰常|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Akitsune|qq=}} – ({{ill|Yamaji Akizumi|ja|山路彰善|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaji Akizumi|qq=}})
; Yoshida Family : {{ill|Sasaki Nagahide|ja|佐々木長秀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sasaki Nagahide|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, later {{ill|Yoshida Nagahide|ja|吉田秀長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Nagahide|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, became Tenmonkata in [[:en:Meiwa|Meiwa]] 1 (1764). : {{ill|Yoshida Nagahide|ja|吉田秀長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Nagahide|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀升|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Hideaki|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀賢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Hideaki|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} – {{ill|Yoshida Hideaki|ja|吉田秀茂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida Hideaki|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}
== Observatories == The first observatory, '''Sitendai''', was established in [[:en:Jōkyō|Jōkyō]] 2 (1685) in {{ill|Ushigome Wakamachi|ja|牛込藁町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ushigome Wakamachi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. It moved to [[:en:Surugadai|Kanda Surugadai]] in [[:en:Genroku|Genroku]] 14 (1701) and later to [[:en:Asakusa|Asakusa]]. In [[:en:Tenpō|Tenpō]] 13 (1842), a second observatory was established in {{ill|Kudanzaka|ja|九段坂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kudanzaka|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 九段}}. Both were abolished in [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 2 (1869).
== Abolition of the Tenmonkata == After the {{ill|Taisei Hōkan|ja|大政奉還|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taisei Hōkan|qq=}}, responsibility for calendrical work returned to the {{ill|Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado family|qq=}}. In [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 3 (1870), calendrical duties were transferred to the Ministry of Education's {{ill|Astronomical Bureau|ja|天文暦道局|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Astronomical Bureau|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.
